text_blocks.text:
The CARICOM Energy Policy (2013) is a wide-ranging framework document that considers issues of energy production and consumption (both renewable and non-renewable programmes) from a regional perspective. The issue of trade between territories and the impacts of programmes such as Petro Caribe are discussed in this policy. However, it should be noted that Barbados was not a signatory to the Petro Caribe agreement. The main goals of the CARICOM Energy Policy are:
* provision of sustainable and secure supplies of energy, accessible to all CARICOM citizens;
* fundamental transformation of the energy sectors of the Member States of the Community so that they can contribute to the sustainable development of the Community;
* optimisation of domestic production of energy in an environmentally sound manner; and
* facilitation of the growth of internationally competitive regional industries.
